body:
In a module such as the following, the standard would appear to imply that all four blocks should be named `genblk1`. Indeed, this is the behavior I've run into in most simulators.
```Verilog
module top;
         if (P == 1) integer w = 1;
    else if (P == 2) integer x = 2;
    else if (P == 3) integer y = 3;
    else             integer z = 9;
endmodule
```

For the equivalent case statement below, all 4 blocks receive the same implicit name, as expected.
```Verilog
    case (P)
        1      : integer w = 1;
        2      : integer x = 2;
        3      : integer y = 3;
        default: integer z = 9;
    endcase
```

Further, the numbering does not reset as required in nested scopes. In the following snippet, the two nested blocks should be `genblk1` and `genblk2`, respectively, but instead continue the numbering of the outer scope.
```Verilog
    if (1) begin
        wire B = 1;
        if (1) begin
            wire C = 1;
        end
        if (1) begin
            wire D = 1;
        end
    end
```

